ce:section.ce:para:
To further explore the specific binding sites between L-CDs and ctDNA and understand the structural changes in ctDNA under the action of L-CDs, the effects of different concentrations of L-CDs on the FT-IR spectra of ctDNA were analysed in detail. In the infrared absorption range of 1800 ∼ 800 cm−1, we focused on the characteristic absorption peak of ctDNA (Fig. 6
                        ). First, absorption peaks near 1225 cm−1 and 1087 cm−1 were observed, which correspond to the asymmetric and symmetric stretching vibrations of the phosphate-pentose backbone of B-DNA, respectively; these peaks clearly indicate that ctDNA maintains its typical right-handed B-type helical conformation. Second, in the region from 1750 cm−1 to 1500 cm−1, we identified four DNA-specific vibration peaks, which were attributed to the vibrations of adenine (A), thymine (T), cytosine (C) and guanine (G), located near 1609 cm−1, 1653 cm−1, 1506 cm−1 and 1716 cm−1, respectively. In addition, the absorption peaks at 968 cm−1 and 835 cm−1 were related to the C-C and C-O stretching vibrations of deoxyribose and the phosphate diester bond, respectively, which further confirmed the molecular structure of ctDNA. When examining the effect of L-CDs concentration on the ctDNA spectrum, we noted that the absorption peaks at 968 cm−1 and 835 cm−1 did not shift despite the interaction between L-CDs and ctDNA. This indicates that the interaction between L-CDs and ctDNA does not destroy the basic helical structure of ctDNA; that is, the right-handed B-helix conformation of ctDNA is maintained. However, a more detailed analysis revealed more interesting phenomena. Although the stretching vibration peaks of the A and T bases did not change significantly after L-CDs treatment, the stretching vibration bands of the G and C bases redshifted. Redshift usually means that intermolecular interactions lead to a decrease in vibrational energy. Therefore, this finding indicates that there is a strong interaction between L-CDs and the G–C base pair of ctDNA [29]. By studying the difference in the FT-IR spectra of ctDNA before and after the action of L-CDs, we revealed the interaction between L-CDs and specific base pairs of ctDNA. These findings not only enhance our understanding of the interaction mechanism between L-CDs and ctDNA but also provide important clues for further exploring the application potential of L-CDs at the molecular level. See (Fig. 7
                        ).
